% Remarks
% When working with documents in any capacity it is best practice to validate a user's permission to the a document. User permissions can be defined in multiple places throughout the OnBase configuration and may not necessarily be obvious to a developer. Using the CanI method on the DocumentType object will help in increasing performance and reduce round trip calls to the Application server and database are not made.

% Accessing Document PageData (physical file bytes) is dependent on the Rendition that is being retrieved for export. Because a Document may contain multiple rendition it is necessary to know if the document's DocumentType configuration is setup to allow multiple renditions. Knowing this information will assist in the design of the application or Unity Script. For simplicity, using the DefaultRenditionOfLatestRevision property will always return the default rendition. The default rendition is defined by the DocumentType's configured File Format. For more information about configuring Document Types refer to the System Administrators Guide.

% The DataProviders are designed to allow documents to be retrieved in various other formats. For example, if there is a requirement provide users with PDF versions it is possible. Using the PDFDataProvider, documents will be retrieved as PDF documents. The PDFDataProvider does not change how the document is physically stored with OnBase. So, if the document is stored in OnBase as an image, the PDFDataProvider will convert the document 'on-the-fly'. This conversion is completely transparent to the end-user.

% ImageGetDocumentProperties provides additional attributes associated with the retrieval a document. These attributes provide some added flexibility. For example, text based documents that are imported through a process such as COLD, AFP, or DJDE processor may require the use of an overlay to ensure that the data is presented in a more user-friendly format. Overlays are typically applied when a document is displayed within one of OnBase Client. The ImageGetDocumentProperties can be used to apply the overlay at the time of retrieval. Other attributes include any notes that may be associated, setting the DPI and page ranges.

% ImageContentType is used for image documents only. It provides an enumeration of image style types. This is useful if you need to return rendered images in a way other than their stored format. Image documents can be returned in one of four (4) format styles: TIFF, TIFF Group IV, TIFF Lossless or JPG.

