% Document Queries are one of the fundamental features of OnBase. They are the primary way to retrieving a document from OnBase and allows a developer to customize the search criteria to ensure that proper documents are returned.

% Query Types
% There are two (2) ways to query for documents within OnBase

% Document Handle
% Searching documents by the Document Id or handle is the simplest form of search. Although this method is the simplest it is also restricted to returning only one document per execution and requires that the document id/handle is already known. If the id/handle is not known it will be up to the developer to provide some additional methods to retrieve the document.

% Advanced Query
% The Document Query is a more advanced, criteria based method for retrieving documents. Document Queries extend the functionality of querying by providing the ability to incorporate the use of OnBase Custom Queries that are built and maintained in the OnBase Configuration module. This can be an advantage for developers to design the ability of a document query that can be managed by non-developer end-users. Unlike the Document Handle method, the Document Query can be used to return one or many documents in a single query execution.

% The document query offers multiple options to include additional metadata (e.g., Keywords, Notes, Revisions, etc...) within the query request. These additional options are designed to increase performance and reduce the number of calls to the OnBase database.

% Additional Notes
% Query Execution
% Document Queries can be complex and often times misunderstood. There are several items of note that should be covered when working with Document Queries as there may be times when then need to be adjusted for either performance or simplicity.

% Understanding the execution of Document Queries can be crucial to the performance. There are two (2) methods that can be used when executing Document Queries.

% Execute: Designed for small Document subset retrievals. This method returns all results in a single response from the server.

% ExecuteQueryResults: Designed for larger results sets and for adding search criteria that is not natively part of standard document metadata. This method will chunk the result response and provide one hundred and fifty (150) results at a time.

% General best practice suggests that the ExecuteQueryResults method be used in most cases. Even with smaller queries the ExecutQueryResults is a more efficient method of handling the Document Query response.

% Query with Keywords
% When creating document query and using keywords to narrow the search it is important to know about searching for NULL or keywords that have not been assigned a value on a document.

% The short answer, it is not possible. Why? Since OnBase is a database driven application, keywords and there values are associated with a particular document which is stored in the database. However, if a value has not been assigned to a Keyword associated to a Document then there would be no row in the database to identify that particular Keyword. So, when working with a document query it would not be possible to search for a NULL or keyword without an associated value as it would not exists in the database and therefore not provide anything to search.

% Although, finding documents that do not have a keyword associated is still possible. Using the ExecuteQueryResults method allow the ability to include additional parameters to the query returning keywords without an associated value. Please refer to *placeholder*.

